## Suggested First Implementation Sprint

### Sprint Goal

Prove a stateless TypeScript SDK client can update a file in a Git repository through TreeDB and receive a commit SHA, without cloning the repository locally.

### Scope

* Phoenix service skeleton.
* Repository registration.
* Workspace create/close.
* File read/write/status/diff/commit.
* Minimal `TreeDbClient` in `packages/ts-sdk`.
* One end-to-end test.

### Out of Scope

* Graph indexing.
* Content model semantics.
* Remote shell.
* Snapshots.
* Market UI.
* Production sandboxing.

### Sprint Acceptance Test

```ts
const client = new TreeDbClient({ baseUrl, repoId, defaultActor });

const workspace = await client.createWorkspace({
  baseRef: "main",
  branchName: "agent/demo-update",
  mode: "writable",
  allowedPaths: ["src/content/**"]
});

await client.writeFile({
  workspaceId: workspace.id,
  path: "src/content/knowledge/demo.mdx",
  content: "---\ntitle: Demo\n---\n\nUpdated by TreeDB.\n"
});

const diff = await client.diff({ workspaceId: workspace.id });

const commit = await client.commit({
  workspaceId: workspace.id,
  message: "Update demo knowledge through TreeDB"
});

expect(commit.commitSha).toBeTruthy();
expect(commit.changedPaths).toContain("src/content/knowledge/demo.mdx");
```

This sprint proves the core storage/scaling thesis before adding semantic content, graph, shell, or market workflows.

